{"title_page": "Bob Feldman", "text_new": "'''Robert C. Feldman''' (born June 14, 1940) is an American songwriter and record producer, best known for his work in the 1960s with fellow writers [[Jerry Goldstein (producer)|Jerry Goldstein]] and [[Richard Gottehrer]], including \"[[My Boyfriend's Back (song)|My Boyfriend's Back]]\", \"[[I Want Candy]]\", and \"[[Sorrow (The McCoys song)|Sorrow]]\".\n\n==Life and career==\nFeldman was born in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]].  He was raised in an [[Orthodox Jewish]] home and briefly studied to become a [[cantor]].  He graduated from [[Abraham Lincoln High School (Brooklyn)|Abraham Lincoln High School]] alongside [[Neil Sedaka]], and was a member of the All-City Choir alongside [[Neil Diamond]] and [[Barbra Streisand]].  Together with his friend and neighbor Jerry Goldstein, he was a dancer on [[Alan Freed]]'s [[WNEW-TV]] show ''The Big Beat'', and in 1959 the pair co-wrote a theme song for the show.  Feldman and Goldstein started writing regularly together, and, as Bob and Jerry, wrote and recorded \"We Put the Bomp\", an [[answer record]] to [[Barry Mann]]'s \"[[Who Put the Bomp (in the Bomp, Bomp, Bomp)|Who Put the Bomp]]\".<ref name=books/><ref name=selvin>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-Mc3BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA265&lpg=PA265&dq=%22Big+Beat%22+Freed+Feldman&source=bl&ots=EojMinRZOR&sig=ACfU3U13Ujno6_lr8nQyctnaFXphL5bDcw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiT6JCAmNbnAhXUuHEKHXnjA68Q6AEwAHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Big%20Beat%22%20Freed%20Feldman&f=false  Joel Selvin, ''Here Comes the Night: The Dark Soul of Bert Berns and the Dirty Business of Rhythm and Blues'', Counterpoint, 2014, pp.265-267]</ref>\n\nIn 1962, they met fellow songwriter Richard Gottehrer, and formed FGG Productions.  Feldman said: \"I was the dreamer, Jerry was the schemer and Richie was the voice of reason\".<ref name=finnis>[https://www.bobfeldmanmusic.net/about Rob Finnis, \"About Bob Feldman\", ''Bob Feldman Music'', 2012]. Retrieved 16 February 2020</ref> The trio wrote several hit singles together, including \"[[My Boyfriend's Back (song)|My Boyfriend's Back]]\" by [[The Angels (American group)|The Angels]].  In 1964, in response to the \"[[British Invasion]]\", they formed their own group, [[The Strangeloves]], who had hits with \"[[I Want Candy]]\", \"Cara-Lin\", and \"[[Night Time (song)|Night Time]]\".   With Goldstein and Gottehrer, Feldman also co-wrote \"[[Sorrow (The McCoys song)|Sorrow]]\" &ndash; first recorded by [[The McCoys]] and later a hit for both [[The Merseys]] and [[David Bowie]] &ndash; and \"Gonna Make It Alone\", recorded by [[Dion DiMucci|Dion]] and by [[Ronnie Dio and the Prophets]].  The three also [[record production|produced]] the McCoys' hit \"[[Hang On Sloopy]]\".<ref name=books/><ref name=selvin/><ref name=vf>[https://www.musicvf.com/songs.php?page=artist&artist=Bob+Feldman&tab=songaswriterchartstab  Songs written by Bob Feldman, ''MusicVF.com'']. Retrieved 16 February 2020</ref>\n  \nIn 1966, Feldman and Goldstein moved to California to set up their own office, and also recorded together as the duo Rome & Paris.  Feldman later worked as a record producer with [[Link Wray]], [[The Belmonts]], and others.  In the 1990s, he moved to [[Nashville]],<ref name=ap>[https://apnews.com/e395321d5cb175d57080402bac27c373  Jim Patterson, \"Nashville Sound: Bob Feldman\", ''AP News'', March 26, 1998]. Retrieved 16 February 2020</ref> and in 2002 co-wrote [[Dusty Drake]]'s debut [[country music|country]] hit, \"And Then\".<ref name=vf/> In 2019, he published a book of verse, lyrics and memoirs, ''Simply Put!: Thoughts and Feelings from the Heart''.<ref name=books>[https://booksandbooks.com/event/bob-feldman/ \"Bob Feldman: About the Author\", ''Books & Books'', 2019]. Retrieved 16 February 2020</ref>\n \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feldman, Bob}}\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n", "text_old": "'''Robert C. Feldman''' (born June 14, 1940) is an American songwriter and record producer, best known for his work in the 1960s with fellow writers [[Jerry Goldstein (producer)|Jerry Goldstein]] and [[Richard Gottehrer]], including \"[[My Boyfriend's Back (song)|My Boyfriend's Back]]\", \"[[I Want Candy]]\", and \"[[Sorrow (The McCoys song)|Sorrow]]\".\n\n==Life and career==\nFeldman was born in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]].  He was raised in an [[Orthodox Jewish]] home and briefly studied to become a [[cantor]].  He graduated from [[Abraham Lincoln High School (Brooklyn)|Abraham Lincoln High School]] alongside [[Neil Sedaka]], and was a member of the All-City Choir alongside [[Neil Diamond]] and [[Barbra Streisand]].  Together with his friend and neighbor Jerry Goldstein, he was a dancer on [[Alan Freed]]'s [[WNEW-TV]] show ''The Big Beat'', and in 1959 the pair co-wrote a theme song for the show.  Feldman and Goldstein started writing regularly together, and, as Bob and Jerry, wrote and recorded \"We Put the Bomp\", an [[answer record]] to [[Barry Mann]]'s \"[[Who Put the Bomp (in the Bomp, Bomp, Bomp)|Who Put the Bomp]]\".<ref name=books/><ref name=selvin>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-Mc3BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA265&lpg=PA265&dq=%22Big+Beat%22+Freed+Feldman&source=bl&ots=EojMinRZOR&sig=ACfU3U13Ujno6_lr8nQyctnaFXphL5bDcw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiT6JCAmNbnAhXUuHEKHXnjA68Q6AEwAHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Big%20Beat%22%20Freed%20Feldman&f=false  Joel Selvin, ''Here Comes the Night: The Dark Soul of Bert Berns and the Dirty Business of Rhythm and Blues'', Counterpoint, 2014, pp.265-267]</ref>  \n\nIn 1962, they met fellow songwriter Richard Gottehrer, and formed FGG Productions.  Feldman said: \"I was the dreamer, Jerry was the schemer and Richie was the voice of reason\".<ref name=finnis>[https://www.bobfeldmanmusic.net/about Rob Finnis, \"About Bob Feldman\", ''Bob Feldman Music'', 2012]. Retrieved 16 February 2020</ref> The trio wrote several hit singles together, including \"[[My Boyfriend's Back (song)|My Boyfriend's Back]]\" by [[The Angels (American group)|The Angels]].  In 1964, in response to the \"[[British Invasion]]\", they formed their own group, [[The Strangeloves]], who had hits with \"[[I Want Candy]]\", \"Cara-Lin\", and \"[[Night Time (song)|Night Time]]\".   With Goldstein and Gottehrer, Feldman also co-wrote \"[[Sorrow (The McCoys song)|Sorrow]]\" &ndash; first recorded by [[The McCoys]] and later a hit for both [[The Merseys]] and [[David Bowie]] &ndash; and \"Gonna Make It Alone\", recorded by [[Dion DiMucci|Dion]] and by [[Ronnie Dio and the Prophets]].  The three also [[record production|produced]] the McCoys' hit \"[[Hang On Sloopy]]\".<ref name=books/><ref name=selvin/><ref name=vf>[https://www.musicvf.com/songs.php?page=artist&artist=Bob+Feldman&tab=songaswriterchartstab  Songs written by Bob Feldman, ''MusicVF.com'']. Retrieved 16 February 2020</ref>\n  \nIn 1966, Feldman and Goldstein moved to California to set up their own office, and also recorded together as the duo Rome & Paris.  Feldman later worked as a record producer with [[Link Wray]], [[The Belmonts]], and others.  In the 1990s, he moved to [[Nashville]],<ref name=ap>[https://apnews.com/e395321d5cb175d57080402bac27c373  Jim Patterson, \"Nashville Sound: Bob Feldman\", ''AP News'', March 26, 1998]. Retrieved 16 February 2020</ref> and in 2002 co-wrote [[Dusty Drake]]'s debut [[country music|country]] hit, \"And Then\".<ref name=vf/> In 2019, he published a book of verse, lyrics and memoirs, ''Simply Put!: Thoughts and Feelings from the Heart''.<ref name=books>[https://booksandbooks.com/event/bob-feldman/ \"Bob Feldman: About the Author\", ''Books & Books'', 2019]. Retrieved 16 February 2020</ref>\n \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feldman, Bob}}\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1